Name: Landsman, Greg
text:
Number 1: 

A new governing document: A Pledge to America 
 
We need a new governing document that explains to the American people how we're going to fix the economy, how we're going to keep people safe, how we're going to fix democracy, the government, everything.

Here’s how…

Name: Landsman, Greg
text:
In 1994, Republicans introduced the Contract with America—10 bills they’d pass if they won the majority.

They were very successful.

Name: Landsman, Greg
text:
1. Reward Hard Work, Not Wealth Act: This is the alternative to the terrible budget bill they just passed.

It would fix the tax code, making sure that everybody at the top pays all their taxes. Then, we can provide meaningful tax relief for the working folks, small businesses, farmers, and the middle class.

Name: Landsman, Greg
text: Ours — the “Pledge to America” includes 10 bills will fundamentally fix what’s broken.

Name: Landsman, Greg
text:
2. The Build Baby Build Bill: Yes, that’s a lot. But we need to build again: More housing, more infrastructure, more broadband. 

All so we can have lower rent, lower housing costs, and better access.

Name: Landsman, Greg
text: It would lower costs significantly by requiring full transparency for insurance companies, pharmaceutical companies, hospitals, AND it would get us back into negotiating lower prescription drug prices across the board.

Name: Landsman, Greg
text: 3. Improve Care, Lower Costs Act: This is the bill that would expand access to health care. It would create a public option and allow people to buy into Medicare.

Name: Landsman, Greg
text:
4. Improve Education Act: No party has had a real plan to improve education in decades.

This bill invests in early childhood—from prenatal care and paid leave to preschool—so every kid shows up to kindergarten ready.

It also makes college and the trades more accessible and affordable.

Name: Landsman, Greg
text:
5. Improve the Federal Government Act: This is really important. It would require independent audits for EVERY agency and create a binding vote to tackle any waste, fraud, and abuse in the audit.

Equally as important, it would require a number of anti-corruption measures.

Name: Landsman, Greg
text: 6. Fix Our Democracy Act or the John Lewis Voting Rights Act: End voter suppression, partisan gerrymandering, and dark money. Stop politicians from buying and selling stocks.

Name: Landsman, Greg
text:
7. 21st Century Anti-Crime Bill:
Communities across the country, particularly cities, are really struggling with gun violence. They need more police officers and they need real gun reform – this bill would do that.

Name: Landsman, Greg
text: 8. Restoring Personal Liberties Act: Protect personal autonomy—from reproductive freedom, LGBTQ rights, and more.

Name: Landsman, Greg
text:
9. Border Security & Immigration Reform Act: This bill includes a ton of bipartisan measures: additional Border Patrol officers, more judges, asylum reform…

and perhaps most importantly, legal pathways for Dreamers and for folks who have been working here.

Name: Landsman, Greg
text:
Second big thing: We need a new national entity — a group of people and leadership who are fully dedicated to this moment.

We need it to reframe the narrative and meet the moment fully.

Name: Landsman, Greg
text:
10. Strengthening America’s Global Leadership Act: This would reaffirm our alliances, fight authoritarianism, and promote democracy and trade.

Also, this bill would reinvest in the foreign aid we know is so critical to our national security – and just us as human beings.

Name: Landsman, Greg
text:
It needs to have the moral seriousness and political discipline of the Civil Rights movement, so people all over the country know what they’re seeing is really bad.

BUT there’s a better way forward—and we can get there.

These are the two big things I believe will help us fix what they’ve broken.

Name: Meuser, Daniel
text:
I had a great evening at the Schuylkill County Fair—one of our region’s longest-running summer traditions. I even got behind the wheel for the Celebrity Tractor Pull, always a crowd favorite and a lot of fun! 

Thanks to Paul Kennedy, who’s led the Fair Association for more than a decade, for taking the time to walk me through the grounds and show me what’s new this year. Since 1984, the Fair has brought the community together to celebrate our agricultural roots, showcase student achievements in 4-H and FFA, and support local organizations and small businesses.

I was glad to treat this year’s Fair Royalty to milkshakes and to donate an American flag that had been flown over the U.S. Capitol—a small token of appreciation for a fair that means so much to this community.

It was a pleasure to meet and talk with so many constituents throughout the night. My thanks to all the dedicated volunteers who work year after year to make the Fair a success.

Name: Blunt Rochester, Lisa
text:
Tonight, I voted for two resolutions to suspend further military aid and arms sales to Israel. The ongoing humanitarian crisis in Gaza is unconscionable. The seemingly deliberate bombing of civilian infrastructure, the alleged killing of Gazan civilians seeking food aid, the man-made famine among the Palestinian people, the increased presence of illegal settlers and violence in the West Bank, the killing of an American citizen without an impartial investigation, and the continued refusal to responsibly work toward a two-state solution all underscore the unacceptable decisions being made by the Israeli government.
 
I have long been a supporter of Israel's right to exist and defend itself from terrorism. I have also repeatedly called for the release of hostages being held by Hamas. My votes tonight underscore the importance of finding peace in the region, and a lasting ceasefire in Gaza that puts an end to the civilian casualties is the best way to achieve that.
 
Until Israel significantly shifts its military posture to end the dire humanitarian crisis in Gaza and the West Bank, I cannot in good conscience support further military aid and arms sales to Israel. It is critical that the Israeli government resume the adequate flow of humanitarian aid into Gaza, stop the senseless bombing, and work with the United States and our international partners to secure a lasting ceasefire and end this war.

Tonight, I voted in favor of blocking the Trump Administration from sending more weapons to Israel.

Enough is enough.

I’ve long pressed the Netanyahu Administration in public and private to take substantive steps to alleviate the suffering of innocent civilians. But conditions on the ground are getting worse, not better. 

Israel’s unacceptable choice to restrict humanitarian and food aid from entering Gaza—for months—is now causing innocent civilians, including young children, to starve to death. Ending this famine is not only a moral imperative, it is also in the best interests of both Israel’s and our own country’s long-term national security.
 
While I have always supported Israel’s right to defend itself and protect the Israeli people, these dire circumstances must end. 

My votes tonight reflect my deep frustration with the Netanyahu government’s abject failure to address humanitarian needs in Gaza and send a message to the Trump Administration that it must change course if it wants to help end this devastating war.

🚨 Confirmation update—

At 10:45pm last night, we finished: confirming Gaisser and Kent, and invoked cloture on Clarkson and two more nominees (at Homeland & US Marshals). 

This morning, we'll advance Cheryl Mason for Inspector General at the VA, then confirm Tyler Clarkson for GC at @USDA.

Name: Smith, Adam
text:
William Galston’s op-ed in the Wall Street Journal acknowledges a hard truth: Hamas will never surrender. That truth underscores the urgent need for a fundamental shift in strategy. After nearly two years of war, it’s clear that the complete destruction of Hamas is not a feasible or sustainable goal and the cost of continuing to try is far too high.

Hamas is a terrorist organization and bears full responsibility for the horrific October 7 attacks. But continuing this war indefinitely, with devastating consequences for innocent Palestinian civilians, will not bring peace or security to Israel or the region.

There are Palestinians who reject Hamas’s violence and extremism and they must be empowered to lead. A new path forward is the only way to achieve long-term peace and security. The current course of continued military operations, displacement, and indefinite occupation risks even greater instability, can undermine key regional partnerships, and diminishes Israel’s moral and strategic standing.

It is time for an immediate ceasefire to address the humanitarian crisis and for Israel to accept a permanent ceasefire in exchange for the return of the remaining hostages. Israel must begin working with the United States, Arab partners, and the international community to support credible Palestinian alternatives to Hamas to govern Gaza and the West Bank.

We can continue to support Israel’s right to defend itself while recognizing that the military campaign has reached its limits. The time has come to shift from endless war to a political strategy that brings hostages home, delivers humanitarian relief, and builds the foundations for lasting peace. The United States must lead that effort.

Name: Greene, Marjorie Taylor
text:
Yesterday I spoke to a Christian pastor from Gaza.

There are children starving. 

And Christians have been killed and injured, as well as many innocent people. 

If you are an American Christian, this should be absolutely unacceptable to you. 

Just as we said that Hamas killing and kidnapping innocent people on Oct 7th is absolutely unacceptable.

Are innocent Israeli lives more valuable than innocent  Palestinian and Christian lives?

And why should America continue funding this?

The secular government of nuclear armed Israel has proven that they are beyond capable of dealing with their enemies and are capable  of and are in the process of systematically cleansing them from the land. 

Most Americans that I know don’t hate Israel and we are not antisemitic at all.

We are beyond fed up with being told that we have to fix the world’s problems, pay for the world’s problems, and fight all the world’s wars while Americans are struggling to survive even though they work everyday.

And many of us, even though we are Christians, no longer want to fund and fight nuclear armed secular Israel’s wars especially when it leads to starving children and killing innocent people including Christians.

Of course we are against radical Islamic terrorism, but we are also against genocide.

You see..

When you have worked your entire life, and will only receive a $1,000 Social Security check, but noncitizens were given $3,500 and more, you are pissed off.

When you have worked your entire life, and all your elected federal officials have recklessly spent and sent your hard earned money to every foreign country and every foreign war and NGO to the point we are almost $40 TRILLION in debt and inflation has caused life to be unaffordable, you are pissed off.

When you have worked your entire life, and your elected federal government officials refuse to fix the absurd problems that makes all insurance unaffordable, you are pissed off.

And for the younger generations, who are trying their hardest to make it in this ridiculous system, they feel hopeless! 

And that makes me burn with anger.

None of this is antisemitic and I, along with millions of Americans, refuse that manipulative label.

It’s the consequences of decades of America LAST policies, nonstop foreign intervention, and the American people clearly seeing the truth and suffering.

Here is where I stand.

No American should face persecution of any kind because of their identity.

Not Jewish American.

Not Muslim American.

Not Christian American.

Not White, Black, Asian, Hispanic, mixed American.

And on and on.

We already have hate crime laws against that and that’s not who we are in America and we have and should continue to work hard to not allow ourselves to become that.

My position is this.

As a U.S. Representative, I represent the American people. 

My full focus is on fixing America’s problems.

And right now, the problems in America are threatening my children’s future.

I consider that a war against my children.

Every single person, no matter who they are that continues to enslave my children in debt, continues policies that make their lives unaffordable, and prioritizes foreign countries and foreign wars above my children’s lives and livelihoods, I see as the enemy waging the war against my children and their generation.

I will continue to push for world peace because that is the type of world I want for my children and all the world’s children.

I want America to put American companies and American jobs first and to protect American land and American homes from foreign consumption. 

Most importantly, I demand the federal government serve the American people, who pay your salaries.

September 30th brings another annual government funding deadline. 

I sincerely hope Republicans, out on August recess right now, will return in September with a renewed focus to stop funding foreign wars and stop waging the fiscal war against my children and their entire generation.

Name: Escobar, Veronica
text:
🚨 Donald Trump instructed Texas Republicans to engage in a power grab by re-drawing congressional districts in our state. 
 
Now that they’ve published the heavily-gerrymandered map, I’ve heard from a lot of you over the last 24 hours so let’s break down your questions 🧵

Name: Escobar, Veronica
text:
“Why is Trump doing this?”
 
Midterm elections happen next year, and he’s worried that Republicans who voted to gut your healthcare to pay for tax breaks for millionaires with his “big, beautiful bill” will lose their races. So he wants to rig the next election via redistricting.

Name: Escobar, Veronica
text:
“How does the proposal affect El Paso?”
 
The map strips major parts of El Paso County, all of Fort Bliss, our airport, and the new VA Health Care Center (that I was able to secure $700 million in funding for) from our boundary and gives it to a Republican 500+ miles away.

Name: Escobar, Veronica
text:
“Okay but why does that matter?”
 
Representation matters. If your new Congressman doesn’t care much about El Paso, he won’t work to bring resources back to the community or work to help you.

Name: Escobar, Veronica
text:
It’s easier for him to vote against our interests because he’s not around very much. 

Has he ever even held a town hall in east El Paso to hear from constituents?

Name: Escobar, Veronica
text:
“I want that Republican representative being my member of congress.”

You can vote for a Republican or a Democrat, but you’re not picking your politician here – quite the opposite. This politician is picking you. And he’ll be hundreds of miles away from you.

Name: Escobar, Veronica
text:
“Can’t you still work for the areas in El Paso you won’t represent?”
 
I will of course try, but each member of Congress has an obligation and a responsibility to focus on the people and assets within their districts.

Name: Escobar, Veronica
text:
“I don’t like that you prefer immigrants over citizens! I’d rather have a Republican represent me.”
 
I work for El Paso, period. I bring home resources that help veterans, small businesses, local governments and more. I’m proud of my record of delivering for our community.

Name: Escobar, Veronica
text:
Check out a sampling of my record 👇🏽

https://t.co/OWlg1Pd5kj

And feel free to compare that record with the Republican Congressman who lives in San Antonio and already represents part of El Paso.

Name: Escobar, Veronica
text:
“I just want to be seen or feel represented.”
 
We all do, which is why I encourage you to sign up for my newsletter, attend my mobile office hours around the community, or participate in my in-person or virtual town hall meetings.

Name: Escobar, Veronica
text:
There’s still time for you to voice your opinions. 
 
Tomorrow, the Texas House Committee in charge of redistricting will hold a public hearing. You can learn more here 👇🏽
 
https://t.co/vRexqzCiFr

Name: Ivey, Glenn
text:
As National Parks Month comes to a close, I want to encourage you to take time to visit the incredible parks we have right here in Prince George’s County — and all across our country.

One of our hidden gems is Oxon Cove Park — a peaceful place where you can walk, connect with nature, and even pet the animals. But it's more than just beautiful land. It’s a place with deep, complicated history.

Watch my video below.

Not far from Washington, D.C., this land was once worked by enslaved people. That’s part of our story — and we can't look away from it.

Right now, some are trying to erase uncomfortable truths from our classrooms and communities. But we must tell the full story of our country — the good, the bad, and everything in between — so we can learn, grow, and make sure we never repeat the mistakes of the past.

Our national parks are more than pretty landscapes. They are living classrooms, places of healing, and a reflection of who we are — and who we want to be.

Let’s preserve them, protect them, and make sure they remain a powerful part of our future.
https://t.co/r8kmanT8iT

Name: Nadler, Jerrold
text: I proudly joined @RepCasten and over 90 of my colleagues in demanding @SecRubio immediately investigate Trump’s Gaza Humanitarian Fund and surge aid into Gaza.

Name: Nadler, Jerrold
text:
Yet, the Trump State Department has rushed a $30 million award to fund GHF, and in the process waived 9 mandatory counterterrorism and anti-fraud safeguards, and overrode 58 objections from USAID staff. These objections included raising serious concerns about GHF’s lack of experience, weak internal controls, and safety protocols.
 
I believe in an all-of-the-above approach. If the GHF can massively reform and allay all concerns of corruption, impropriety, bias, and perpetuating violence on the ground, I believe that it can theoretically be part of the assistance efforts in Gaza—but that cannot be at the cost of the well-established NGO and UN channel. Until then, the GHF cannot be allowed to continue to operate with impunity. The people of Gaza are crying out for basic humanitarian assistance, and it is the obligation of the United States to make sure that our assistance is, at minimum, doing more good than harm. The GHF brutality dramatically fails that standard. We must demand better for our assistance and ensure that our aid is not subject to the depraved politics of the Trump administration.

Name: Nadler, Jerrold
text: The people of Gaza are experiencing an unspeakable humanitarian catastrophe. Instead of alleviating suffering, the Trump administration has further exacerbated the crisis by seeking to uproot the admittedly imperfect but nonetheless effective assistance U.N. and NGO delivery system designed under the Biden Administration, and implement its own shady and potentially corrupt organization called the Gaza Humanitarian Fund (GHF). Earlier this month, two whistleblowers came forward, and accused the GHF of heinous and abhorrent conduct. They detailed the use of live ammunition, stun grenades, and pepper spray regularly fired into crowds of desperate and hungry Palestinians at GHF aid distribution sites, resulting in countless injuries and deaths. Some reports indicated that as many as 800 Palestinians have been killed while seeking aid at GHF sites. As a UNICEF spokesperson commented about GHF, “these are not humanitarians, they are people with guns.”

Name: Clarke, Yvette D.
text: Today, I join my fellow New Yorkers in expressing my deep condolences to the family and loved ones of New York Police Department Officer Didarul Islam, as well as to each of our Bangladeshi neighbors who are mourning the loss of a true community hero. Officer Islam’s story was not unlike that of many New Yorkers across our city. He migrated to this nation in search of opportunity and possibility, found work serving his city, and raised a family he cherished with all his heart. He was a good man who exemplified everything an officer of the NYPD should aspire to be, and his passing in the line of duty during Monday’s senseless mass shooting is a tragedy in every sense of the word. My heartfelt sympathy and prayers go out to his expecting wife, their two young children, and the entire Bangladeshi-American Community in this time of terrible grief.

Name: Meuser, Daniel
text:
Today I joined several state legislators and industry leaders for a tour of two groundbreaking facilities in Susquehanna County that are turning produced water—the waste byproduct of fracking—into something of strategic value: lithium.

At Avonlea’s Kendra II site in Springville and Gradiant/C2G’s facility in Montrose, we saw how private-sector innovation is transforming what was once discarded into a domestic supply of critical minerals.

This is how we secure energy dominance, reduce reliance on China, and create new jobs. Pennsylvania is leading the way in critical mineral innovation.

Thank you to PA State Rep. Jonathan Fritz for organizing today’s tour and roundtable.

Name: Fine, Randy
text:
Appreciate the 2,500 Rabbis of the Coalition for Jewish Values @cjvalues!   Together, we will fight Muslim terror and the "Jews" and "Jewish groups" who apologize for it.  

-------

The Coalition for Jewish Values (CJV), representing over 2,500 traditional, Orthodox rabbis in matters of public policy, today expressed its support and solidarity with Rep. Randy Fine (R-FL), after the latter was accused of favoring “starving children,” accusations CVJ called "dishonest" and "outrageous." 

"Fine simply pointed out that it is the responsibility of the Hamas terror organization to release the Israeli hostages, disarm, and feed its populace. Yet he faced criticism from left-wing media, a congresswoman with a history of antisemitic statements, and, most regrettably, the American Jewish Committee (@AJCGlobal) who declared Fine’s remarks 'unacceptable' and claimed he was focused upon 'scoring political points,'” the organization stated.

According to CJV: "On the contrary, Mr. Fine demonstrated both moral clarity and courage. He has consistently done so, and recently took to wearing a yarmulke (Jewish skullcap) in Congress to demonstrate solidarity with Jewish students afraid to wear one on their college campus. That’s a wrap on our weeklong marathon across the District! From Carnuel and our land grants, to Sandia Pueblo and the @indianpueblo Cultural Center, the City of Albuquerque, UNM, Kirtland Air Force Base and Sandia National Labs, and some of our most important community organizations—we’ve been on the road across our communities.

From the top of Sandia Peak, to the devastatingly dry Rio Grande, and @abqbiopark—we’ve been talking culture, conservation, public lands, and the protection of New Mexico’s lands and waters.  We’ve been diving deep into the history of our communities at the Center for Southwest Research at @UNM, meeting faculty and students at African American Student Services and American Indian Student Services, and meeting with local representatives, businesses, and cultural leaders.  

Every day, we are so honored to do this work and are grateful to every community we spent time with this week. We are more energized than ever to do the work for NM-01!  As we’re also wrapping up our series on protecting voting rights and our democracy across the country, we’ll be bringing the convo home over the coming weeks to discuss how New Mexico is protecting the vote and our communities.

Name: Slotkin, Elissa
text:
Last night I unfortunately missed a vote series on two Joint Resolutions of Disapproval regarding the sale of weapons to Israel.

I have struggled with this Joint Resolution of Disapproval more than any previous votes in the nearly two years since Hamas initiated the attacks of October 7. I represent a state with a large Arab and Muslim population and a large Jewish population. And over these last two years, few issues have been as raw as this one. I have therefore worked very hard to call balls and strikes based on my experience and the facts on the ground, even as most people fall firmly into one side or another, and are often reluctant to consider new information.

I owe it to my state to make clear where I stand: Had I made it back for the vote yesterday, I would have voted yes to block offensive weapons to Israel based on my concerns over lack of food and medicine getting to civilians in Gaza.

I have been a strong supporter of the Jewish State of Israel my whole life. And I still am. But despite the fact that Hamas began this bloody round of conflict—and refuses to release the hostages—the images of emaciated children are hard to turn away from. As are the calls from Michiganders who have friends and family trying to survive in Gaza.

This issue is now widely acknowledged across the political spectrum. Even President Trump this week has expressed concern over the humanitarian situation and urged Prime Minister Netanyahu to ensure the safe delivery of assistance to those in need.

In general, I think these Disapproval votes are a bad way to do foreign policy. The Executive Branch, whether run by Democrats or now Republicans, has the responsibility to set U.S. foreign policy, and to lead negotiations with both allies and adversaries.

But it appears today that the Netanyahu government thinks that there are no limits to what they can do while still receiving U.S. support. And so, I believe a message has to be sent. Should similar votes on offensive weapons come up in the future, I will take them on a case-by-case basis, with the hope of important humanitarian course corrections. I continue to support the U.S.-Israel security relationship and sale of defensive weapons such as the Iron Dome.

My views on this come from my experience of serving three tours in Iraq alongside the U.S. military. It was a very bloody war zone, including terrible violence on U.S. forces and Iraqi civilians, carried out by terrorist groups and militias. But even in the most violent years of the war, the U.S. still had the responsibility to facilitate humanitarian supplies into places like Fallujah. And militaries that can pull off dangerous and complex operations overseas can also ensure aid is safely distributed in occupied areas.

While the leaders of Hamas deserve what they’re getting in response to October 7, and Israel — like any other country in the world — has the right to defend itself, that doesn’t include letting children go hungry. That is despite Hamas’ sick refusal to relent, prevent further destruction, negotiate in good faith and release the hostages.

Lastly, I make this statement today because of my deep concern and conviction for Israel’s long-term security. I believe the Israeli people have the right to live a safe and secure life, free from threat, and chart their own destiny. The Israelis are right to demand the release of all the hostages, living and deceased, immediately and not in stages.

And it has to be said that Israel has dealt with threats to its existence every day since its founding, which is hard for the average American to comprehend. But the actions being taken now by the Netanyahu government threaten the longstanding bipartisan consensus that have helped keep Israel safe since its inception.

No one leader should so significantly threaten the long-term security of the state of Israel. I urge the Trump Administration and the Israeli Prime Minister to get aid in as soon as possible and save lives.

text:
Friday in the First

Liz Reasoner has dedicated more than 30 years to fighting hunger as the executive director of the Food Bank of the Albemarle. As a Hertford resident, Liz has significantly impacted serving food-insecure communities throughout the region. Her leadership has fostered a compassionate and mission-driven spirit among staff and volunteers, inspiring others to serve with empathy and purpose.
 
In addition to her professional role, Liz volunteers on the boards of the Albemarle Alliance for Children and Families and the Elizabeth City-Pasquotank Backpack Program, organizations that enhance early childhood development and address weekend hunger among students. Her work ensures that children and families receive meals and experience dignity and hope. Liz’s unwavering commitment continues to uplift communities across northeastern North Carolina.

#FridaySpotlight

Name: Fitzpatrick, Brian K.
text:
🚨 Lyme disease is surging across Bucks and Montgomery Counties—and Pennsylvania now accounts for nearly 30% of all cases nationwide.

This isn’t a surprise. It’s the result of years of warnings that went unheeded. That’s why I’ve been working with local health officials, scientists, and national advocates to lead a strong, sustained federal response.

Here’s what we’re doing:

I’m leading a bipartisan push to modernize how our country prevents, detects, treats, and responds to tick-borne illnesses, including:

✅ Kay Hagan TICK Act Reauthorization – To reestablish a coordinated national strategy
✅ LymeX Authorization Act – To accelerate innovation in diagnostics and treatments
✅ Children Inflicted by Lyme Disabilities Act – To expand protections for kids with chronic Lyme
✅ BITE Act – Creates an AI-powered tick outbreak alert system
✅ Tick Identification Pilot Program – Supports state-level photo-based tracking programs

I’ve also fought to expand Lyme research funding through both the Defense and Health Appropriations bills, to ensure science gets the investment it needs.

But until there’s a cure, prevention is key. As we head into Lyme Disease Awareness Month, here’s how to protect yourself and your family:

• Use EPA-registered repellents (DEET, picaridin, IR3535, oil of lemon eucalyptus)
• Wear light-colored clothing and tuck in your pants/shirt
• Shower within 2 hours of outdoor activity
• Do a full-body tick check—especially behind knees, underarms, hairline, waistband 
• Check pets and gear—ask your vet about year-round tick preventatives

⚠️ Watch for symptoms:
• Bullseye rash (may not always appear)
• Fever, chills, fatigue, joint pain
• In kids: memory issues, joint aches, behavioral changes

🕒 Early detection is key. The sooner it’s caught, the easier it is to treat.

🔗 Read More: https://t.co/J8viTC3pEy

Name: Fitzpatrick, Brian K.
text:
Each week, we share stories of extraordinary individuals across our district whose lives exemplify courage, character, and commitment to something greater than themselves. Today, we honor a true American leader—meet this week’s Hometown Hero, Colonel Eric Swenson of Churchville.
 
A graduate of Council Rock and the United States Military Academy at West Point, Colonel Swenson has spent over 25 years in uniform, serving our nation with honor. He is not only a decorated Army officer and combat veteran—he’s a scholar, strategist, and public servant whose leadership has left an indelible mark both at home and abroad.
 
With a PhD in Industrial Engineering from Penn State, and advanced degrees from the Naval and Army War Colleges, Col. Swenson has led everywhere from the battlefield to the classroom—commanding engineer battalions, shaping military strategy, and mentoring the next generation of Army leaders. As Commander of the Army Corps’ St. Paul District, Col. Swenson led critical infrastructure and recovery efforts across five states.
 
In January, when devastating wildfires tore through Los Angeles County—killing 12 and destroying more than 6,800 structures—Col. Swenson was called in to lead the U.S. Army Corps of Engineers’ emergency response. The scale of destruction was staggering. The grief was raw. Yet under his steady command, the mission became what officials called “the fastest, safest, and most community-integrated cleanup operation in California history.”
 
As U.S. Army Secretary Dan Driscoll put it: “Your team cleared debris, repaired infrastructure, and restored essential services—but what really sets you apart is the trust you built with the community.”
 
Col. Swenson walked side by side with survivors, listened to their stories, stood in the ashes of what they lost, and helped chart a path forward—one phone call, one handshake, one act of compassion at a time.
 
Now preparing to assume command of the U.S. Army Corps’ North Atlantic Division—overseeing critical operations across the Northeast and Europe—Colonel Swenson continues to serve with humility, brilliance, and a deep sense of duty to the American people.
 
Colonel Swenson, Bucks County is proud—and deeply grateful—for your service and the sacrifice your family has shared along the way. Join me in thanking and celebrating this true hometown hero!

Name: Cuellar, Henry
text:
July’s jobs report is a warning sign for families and businesses across South Texas. Job growth is slowing down, unemployment is ticking up, and economic uncertainty continues to grow. Behind the headlines, families are feeling the pressure every day.

The addition of only 73,000 jobs last month – well below expectations – signals a cooling economy that’s straining working families. Long-term unemployment is rising, and crucial industries like manufacturing are shedding jobs. This slowdown is made worse by tariffs and unstable trade policies that drive up costs, making it harder for small businesses to hire, grow, and plan ahead.

Now more than ever, we need policies that keep costs low and opportunities high. That means pursuing stable trade agreements, supporting job creators, and ensuring working families have the economic certainty they need to thrive. In Congress, I remain focused on building an economy that prioritizes communities throughout #TX28.

On this day in history in 1776, members of the Continental Congress formally signed a large, handwritten copy of the Declaration of Independence. 

One month earlier, Congress had passed Richard Henry Lee’s resolution declaring the colonies free and independent. Two days after that resolution, on July 4, Congress approved Thomas Jefferson’s more poetic Declaration of Independence, which was first signed by President John Hancock and quickly sent to printers. A formal, handwritten version was commissioned on July 19 and written by Timothy Matlack.

Name: Fitzpatrick, Brian K.
text:
Some stories stay with you. Luke Tynan’s is one of them.

I first met Luke in 2018. At 19, a diving accident changed everything—paralyzing him from the waist down. But from that moment on, it wasn’t his injury that defined him, it was his strength and unshakable positivity.  

What’s unfolded since isn’t just a story of recovery—it’s a story of determination, of a young man committed to walking again, and a community committed to walking with him. Through it all, Luke has been a source of light—lifting others up even as he faces his own challenges.

Now in its 8th year, the #LukeStrong Tournament in Middletown has become more than just a softball game—it’s a tradition built around a young man’s courage, contagious joy, and ability to bring people together.

Luke, thank you for reminding us what it means to live with purpose. And to our entire #LukeStrong community—thank you for continuing to show the power of unity and support!

Name: Collins, Susan M.
text:
Last night, for the first time since 2018, the Senate passed annual appropriations bills ahead of the August recess. The three bills—covering Military Construction and Veterans Affairs; Agriculture, FDA, and Rural Development; and the Legislative Branch annual appropriations—each passed with overwhelming bipartisan support.

These bills include significant investments for projects across the State of Maine.

At Portsmouth Naval Shipyard, nearly $450 million would support power reliability and water resilience upgrades, along with continued expansion of Multi-Mission Dry Dock #1.

At my request, Congressionally Directed Spending is included for new fire and rescue stations in Belgrade, Marshfield, St. Agatha, St. Albans, Thomaston, and Swan’s Island.

In addition, $10 million is provided for the PFAS Center of Excellence at the University of Maine to advance research and develop solutions to address PFAS contamination in Maine’s food and water systems.

I am pleased that, with the passage of these three bills, the Senate is returning to regular order and exercising its constitutional responsibility for the power of the purse. I look forward to continuing the bipartisan cooperation we demonstrated last night as we work to pass the remaining appropriations bills.

text:
🧵Tuesday marked @NASA's 67th anniversary, and #TeamSoto traveled to Cape Canaveral to tour several cutting-edge operations at @NASAKennedy.

From historic NASA facilities to next-generation commercial space technology, it was a glimpse into the future of space exploration. https://t.co/R6134dCQHn

Name: Soto, Darren
text: We began our visit at the Mobile Launcher, the massive structure that supports rocket assembly, testing, and launch. It’s a critical piece of infrastructure for the @NASAArtemis program and future deep space missions. https://t.co/bG3nwwc4Z8

Name: Soto, Darren
text: Next, we stepped inside the iconic Vehicle Assembly Building (VAB)—a towering national landmark where NASA prepares rockets for launch. It’s still central to the agency’s efforts to send astronauts and equipment deeper into space. https://t.co/fSwivbnhr0

Name: Soto, Darren
text: Additionally, we visited the @blueorigin facility, where we learned about their reusable rocket systems. Designed for vertical takeoff and landing, these vehicles can be flown up to 25 times with minimal refurbishment—pushing the boundaries of innovation. https://t.co/P887XswXP6

Name: Soto, Darren
text: We then visited @SpaceX's HangarX, where refurbished Falcon 9 boosters are inspected and prepared for re-flight. This facility represents a new era of reusability in spaceflight—driving down costs while increasing launch frequency. https://t.co/xPnEsnPOhm

Name: Soto, Darren
text: We wrapped up at @PortCanaveral, where we received an update on port operations & got a look at the SpaceX drone ship—used to recover Falcon 9 boosters after they land at sea. It was a reminder of how every mission is part of an ecosystem of recovery, reuse, and reinvention. https://t.co/U5eHVtuwKG

Name: Soto, Darren

Every morning, thousands of #FL9 constituents drive out to the coast to make miracles happen. From NASA, SpaceX, and Blue Origin to Port Canaveral’s cruise and fishing industries, the Space Coast is a hub of exploration, innovation, inspiration, and fun.

Name: Escobar, Veronica
text:
Today, we remember the 23 lives taken from us on August 3, 2019. We continue to grieve with their families and loved ones, and we honor the impact they each made in this world. 

It is impossible to think of August 3rd without recognizing that this horrific violence did not happen in a vacuum. In the days and years before the shooting, Donald Trump so repeatedly demonized Latinos that the man who drove over 10 hours to target our community believed he was fulfilling the president’s wishes. Trump’s hateful rhetoric created fertile ground for extremists to justify violence against innocent people.

As we remember the victims, we must continue fighting the dehumanizing rhetoric that breeds hate and violence, especially when it’s comes from those in positions of power and influence. Words matter.

There is so much the country can learn from El Paso — our resilience, our kindness, our generosity and warmth. 

May the memories of those lost six years ago be a call to action to pursue the highest ideals of justice, empathy, and above all, love.

Name: Hamadeh, Abraham J.
text:
🇺🇸NEW🇺🇸

Congressman Hamadeh received a situation brief from General Mazloum of the Syrian Democratic Forces (SDF) — the US ally in the fight against ISIS.
 
The Congressman thanked General Mazloum and the interim government of Damascus for their continued assistance in the search for Kayla Mueller’s remains so she can finally be buried where she belongs, in her home state of Arizona.
 
With over 100,000 fighters - both Arabs and Kurds - trained by US-led coalition forces, the SDF is a key part of Syria’s future. For over a decade, it has protected the northeast third of Syria, and established a decentralized model that protects Christians, Arabs, Kurds, and others.
 
The SDF seeks time and space to strengthen their inclusive governance framework in Syria’s interim process.
 
This month, Damascus-SDF negotiations will resume in Paris with Trump Administration support, aimed at moving Syria away from the former regime’s failed approach of intimidation and retaliation and toward a system grounded in protecting the rights and freedom for all.
 
We continue to maintain open channels with all parties in Syria committed to peace.

I joined Fox Report to discuss President Trump’s efforts to restore accountability at the Bureau of Labor Statistics. From April 2023 to March 2024, the agency overstated job growth by 818,000—a 40% error.

Those inflated numbers were used to justify a rate cut just before the 2024 election, which raises serious suspicion. And now the Fed is still relying on that flawed data to make key decisions that affect families and businesses across the country.

When I was Revenue Secretary in Pennsylvania, we fixed bad projections by building better models and restoring trust in the numbers. That’s what BLS must do now. Accurate data is the foundation for responsible economic policy.

Name: Welch, Peter
text:
This July, I introduced bills that focus on lowering costs for working families, improving the disaster recovery process for communities, increasing health care access for patients, and giving our farmers and small business owners a fair shot. 
 
On the anniversaries of the July 2023 and 2024 Vermont floods, I introduced the Disaster AID Act.  It cuts red tape at FEMA so assistance can be distributed more quickly and efficiently to towns hit by flooding, wildfires, tornadoes, or other weather catastrophes. 

I reintroduced the Rural Recovery Act, which provides local USDA Rural Development offices with funding to help rural communities recover after a natural disaster. 

Big Pharma is abusing the patent system to keep prices high, making patients pay more for the prescriptions they need.  I led a bipartisan, bicameral bill to make it easier for more affordable generic and biosimilar drugs to enter the market.  

For our servicemembers, I’m working to prohibit the use of open-air burn pits that have caused life-long health issues for some of our veterans and improve how the burn bit registry can be updated. 
 
The 340B program is a lifeline that helps rural hospitals and health centers access affordable prescription drugs and expand their services.  I introduced legislation to thwart Big Pharma’s push to cut back on the program.  
 
President Trump has been waging an unnecessary and volatile trade war against Canada, the largest trading partner to Vermont and 33 other states.  I introduced a bill to exempt small business owners from the painful tariffs being placed on our northern neighbor.  

Right now, AI companies can build their models without sharing how they're doing it. I reintroduced legislation that gives musicians, writers, and other artists a legal pathway to learn if the work they own is being used by AI companies without proper consent or compensation.  

The so-called ‘One Big Beautiful Bill’ was really one giant handout to Big Pharma and sells out folks using Medicaid.  I led an effort to repeal new out-of-pocket expenses placed on care for our seniors, children, and people with disabilities, and close the loophole that lets drug companies charge more.  

The smaller the farm, the more challenging it is for a dairy farmer to earn and stay recognized as an organic producer.  I reintroduced the O DAIRY Act to provide a safety net for small organic producers facing heavy losses and collect data to help them prepare for the future. 

While President Trump and Republicans are taking from the American people to give tax cuts to billionaires, I’ll continue working to improve the lives of working families in Vermont and across the country.

Name: Fitzpatrick, Brian K.
text:
Five years ago today, we made history.

The Great American Outdoors Act—my bipartisan, landmark legislation—was signed into law, delivering one of the biggest conservation wins in a generation.

It permanently funded the Land and Water Conservation Fund, tackled decades of deferred maintenance in our national parks, and made long-overdue investments in clean air, safe drinking water, and public lands for all.

Here in PA-1, that means more protected green spaces, restored habitats, cleaner streams, and outdoor spaces our families can enjoy for generations. These victories were made possible by working hand-in-hand with our local partners who know our land best.

That same spirit of partnership continues to guide my work forward. In February, I introduced the Delaware River Basin Restoration Program Reauthorization Act—a critical next step, developed hand-in-hand with our local conservation leaders, to protect one of our region’s most vital natural resources. 

We’re lucky to live in one of the more beautiful areas in the country, so today, get outside and enjoy it—and know we’re working every day to protect it.

Name: Lankford, James
text:
We secured MAJOR wins for Oklahoma in one of the first appropriations bills passed since 2023 – the Military Construction and Veterans Affairs (MILCON-VA) bill.

Never heard of it? Here’s why it’s important and what it means for Oklahoma ⬇️

The MILCON-VA bill funds construction on our military bases and programs at the Department of Veterans Affairs. It funds everything from barracks and hangars to VA clinics and hospitals.

It directly impacts the lives of service members, veterans, and their families.

Here’s what I secured for Oklahoma in this year’s bill:

Name: Lankford, James
text: $55 million for the Ammunition Demolition Shop at McAlester Army Ammunition Plant, so munitions can be safely decommissioned.

Name: Lankford, James
text: $54 million for a new Child Development Center at Tinker Air Force Base, supporting military families with high-quality childcare on base.

Name: Lankford, James
text: Encourages the VA to identify and remove barriers to working with private healthcare providers, as well as private-sector professionals, on everything from infrastructure improvements to addressing workforce shortages, to improving access to specialized care and providing a more comprehensive support network.

Name: Lankford, James
text: Prohibits federal agencies from awarding bonuses to contractors that fall short of basic contract standards, are over budget, or behind schedule, unless narrowly justified.

Name: Lankford, James
text: Directs the VA to assess options for modernizing medical records storage and urges against the use of outdated compact discs to deliver medical records to veterans.

Name: Lankford, James
text: Requires the VA to report on how often veterans’ authorizations for community care are revoked and to explain why.

Name: Lankford, James
text: This bill is a big win for Oklahoma military bases, for our veterans, and for the communities that support them.

Our #NJ07 Law Enforcement Hometown Hero this week is Officer Hector Lopez of the Branchburg Police Department.
 
Officer Lopez consistently goes above and beyond in the line of duty. He has played a key role in the apprehension of violent suspects, made arrests involving controlled substances, and serves every day with professionalism and integrity. Beyond his official service, he is committed to building unity in the Branchburg community—from mentoring youth to strengthening trust between law enforcement and residents. 
 
In 2023, Officer Lopez was named Branchburg’s 'Officer of the Year' and he was also recognized as 'Top Cop' in both 2023 and 2024 for his exceptional performance and tireless work ethic. 
 
Thank you, Officer Lopez, for protecting the people of Branchburg and serving as a true role model. It is a privilege to recognize you as one of our 2025 Hometown Heroes.

Name: Cantwell, Maria
text: Five years ago, Congress overwhelmingly passed, and President Trump signed into law, the Great American Outdoors Act which was the most significant land conservation and outdoor recreation bill in half a century. I led the fight with others to write and pass this law, which permanently and fully funded the Land and Water Conservation Fund and invested billions to address long overdue public land maintenance backlogs throughout the State of Washington and around the country. Here in Washington, the law has helped us preserve and expand outdoor recreation opportunities and wildlife habitat in the Central Cascades Forest, Mount St. Helens Forest, and the Yakima Basin watershed. The law is clear that these funds can only be used for continuing to protect, expand, and maintain America’s beloved public lands and natural heritage for the enjoyment of Americans today and for generations to come.

Name: Kennedy, Timothy M.

This #NationalHealthCenterWeek, I stood with the incredible team at Neighborhood Health Center (@nhcwny)  to send a clear message: healthcare is a right, not a privilege.

As a former occupational therapist, and the son and grandson of a nurse, I’ve seen the life-changing impact of quality, accessible care. Community health centers are on the frontlines, keeping our neighborhoods healthy against all odds.

Meanwhile, Trump and Congressional Republicans passed over $1 trillion in healthcare cuts that will leave 17 million Americans uninsured. That’s unacceptable. 285,000 people in WNY rely on Medicaid. One in eight New Yorkers depend on a community health center for care. These are our children, our seniors, our veterans, and our neighbors.

We can’t let them down. I’m calling on my Republican colleagues to #CanceltheCuts. Our families and health centers deserve better.

Additionally, we discussed President Trump’s recent trade agreement with Japan that will Increase market access for Missouri rice farmers for the first time since the 1990s.

Our rice farmers haven’t been treated fairly by other coutries, but I’m proud to be standing side by side with President Trump to give them the access they deserve.

Name: Fulcher, Russ
text:
We had a terrific roundtable discussion in Caldwell with local Idaho business leaders on the pro-growth business tax provisions in H.R. 1, the One Big Beautiful Bill Act. 

This legislation delivers for hard-working Idahoans and Main Street. 

It made the 2017 Tax Cuts and Jobs Act (TCJA) lower tax rates permanent for small businesses, while doubling their deductions on expenses. It also eliminated taxes on tips and overtime pay—a tax measure I was inspired to spearhead in Congress after speaking with a constituent at a town hall meeting in Sandpoint. H.R. 1 is a once in a generation piece of legislation that is pro-worker, pro-growth, pro-investment, and will help usher in a new era of American prosperity.

I am grateful to the U.S. Chamber of Commerce and the Caldwell Chamber of Commerce for facilitating this valuable conversation and for all those who came out!

Name: Smith, Jason
text:
My next Farm Tour stop brought me to Ryan Riley Farms, a fourth‑generation operation growing rice and soybeans in Risco down in New  Madrid County. I heard firsthand how farmers like Ryan are grappling with huge economic pressures.

Since President Trump left office in 2021, commodity prices have plummeted. The price of soybeans is down 28% and the price of rice is down over 10%, all while production costs have stayed high. Farmers like Ryan are why I fight for improved market access for our agricultural products. Increased market access like what was negotiated in President Trump's agreement with Japan is huge, but we also need to fight against unfair trade practices in countries like India and Brazil that keep our rice and soybeans out of their markets. 

We also discussed how the One Big, Beautiful Bill will help, with strengthened ARC/PLC support and tax relief that will benefit family-owned farms. But farmers are still struggling, and I will continue working with President Trump to strengthen our rural communities and ensure our farms and farmers are prioritized.

Name: Fitzpatrick, Brian K.
text:
Strong communities are built on trust, connection, and the commitment to show up—for each other, and for the place we all call home.

That’s the spirit behind National Night Out—and why I introduced a bipartisan resolution today with Congresswoman Norma Torres to officially recognize this tradition across the country.

As someone who’s spent a lifetime in law enforcement, I know public safety isn’t just about responding to emergencies—it’s about building real relationships. And here in PA-1, our officers do exactly that. They don’t just serve our neighborhoods—they’re part of them.

Tonight, we celebrate that bond—not just across the nation, but right here at home. Bring your family, meet your neighbors, thank an officer, and take part in what makes PA-1 such a special community.

📍 Find a National Night Out event near you, including:

👮 Doylestown: 4–8PM @ Central Park
👮 Bristol Twp: 5–8PM @ Municipal Park

I helped fund and support the very first solar-powered #CommunityLighthouse in Broadmoor, @CityofNOLA—so I know firsthand how transformational these projects can be.

I strongly urge the EPA to reverse course. Read my full statement: https://t.co/Eckspbzdiw

Name: Cornyn, John
text: Thank you @GregAbbott_TX for taking the lead in holding Democrats accountable.

Name: Warren, Elizabeth
text:
BREAKING NEWS: a government watchdog confirmed the Trump administration is breaking the law by blocking NIH funds.
 
How many kids with cancer or grandmas with Alzheimer’s have to get closer to death while crucial research is stalled? 

Trump must end this illegal funding freeze. https://t.co/hwwTC7J8Ll

Van Hollen, Chris
text:
The US is right to lift sanctions on Syria & encourage others to do so BUT we must also ensure clear “snap-back” provisions are in place that would be triggered if the govt does not meet key conditions, including measures to protect the rights of religious & ethnic minorities.
 
https://t.co/swMa4Na2X8

Name: Smith, Adam
text: Folks from Puget Sound Advocates for Retirement Action stopped by my district office today to discuss the need to protect Social Security and Medicare. This administration has hurt our country’s most vulnerable, including our retirees, but I’m working to ensure seniors have access to the healthcare and benefits they’ve earned.

Name: Durbin, Richard J.
text:
Joined @OaktonCollege to celebrate the opening of their Health Careers Education Center.

With new federal funds, this project will grow the next generation of health care workers, create long-lasting careers & ensure quality medical care for Illinoisans. https://t.co/UoYYh2N1vz

Name: Mast, Brian J.
text:
FL RESIDENTS: It’s Florida’s “Back to School Sales Tax Holiday” starting today through August 31st. Qualifying clothing, footwear, school supplies, computers and accessories, and learning aids are all tax-free. As we gear up for another school year, now’s the time to get the supplies needed.

MORE: https://t.co/CCEFmwqRn2

Name: Ryan, Patrick
text:
La Guelaguetza is a highlight of Hudson Valley summers, bringing us together to celebrate & share in Oaxacan traditions & culture.

I presented festival organizers with a Congressional Record, etching their invaluable contributions to our community into our nation's history. https://t.co/JNh0A9B7hV

Name: Miller, Mary E.
text:
Taxpayers shouldn’t be forced to fund junk food and sugary drinks that fuel America’s obesity and diabetes crisis.

I’m glad @SecRollins and @SecKennedy are taking action to ensure SNAP benefits provide real nutrition, as intended! https://t.co/pOkmxHFUAV

Name: Dingell, Debbie
text: A potato a day keeps the doctor away... a motto I have always lived by

Name: Garbarino, Andrew R.
text:
I’m grateful to @NassauExec & @NassauCountyPD  for inviting me to the David S. Mack Center for Training and Intelligence. I was thoroughly impressed by this state-of-the-art facility. 

As @HomelandGOP Chairman, I am committed to ensuring law enforcement has the resources, training, and real-time intelligence they need. This is how we protect New York and communities nationwide.
